# Elliptic solvers. ## The elliptic problem for the pressure. The 3D non-hydrostatic pressure field is obtained by taking the divergence of the horizontal ; component of the momentum equations and invoking the vertical component to yield an elliptic ; Poisson equation for the non-hydrostatic kinematic pressure; ```math;  egin{equation}; \label{eq:poisson-pressure}; 
abla^2 p_{NH} =  rac{ oldsymbol{
abla}  oldsymbol{\cdot}  oldsymbol{v}^n}{\Delta t} +  oldsymbol{
abla}  oldsymbol{\cdot}  oldsymbol{G}_{ oldsymbol{v}} \equiv \mathscr{F} \, ,; \end{equation}; ```; along with homogenous Neumann boundary conditions `` oldsymbol{v} \cdot  oldsymbol{\hat{n}} = 0`` ; (Neumann on ``p`` for wall-bounded directions and periodic otherwise) and where ``\mathscr{F}`` ; denotes the source term for the Poisson equation. !!! note "Hydrostatic approximation"; For problems in which the hydrostatic approximation is invoked, the Poisson equation for; pressure above only needs to be solved for the vertically integrated flow and the pressure; field is a two dimensional term ``p_S(x, y, t)``. ## Direct method. Discretizing elliptic problems that can be solved via a classical separation-of-variables approach, such as Poisson's; equation, results in a linear system of equations ``M  oldsymbol{x} =  oldsymbol{y}`` where ``M`` is a real symmetric matrix of block; tridiagonal form. This allows for the matrix to be decomposed and solved efficiently, provided that the eigenvalues and; eigenvectors of the blocks are known (搂2) [Buzbee70](@cite). In the case of Poisson's equation on a rectangle,; [Hockney65](@citet) has taken advantage of the fact that the fast Fourier transform can be used to perform the matrix; multiplication steps resulting in an even more efficient method. [Schumann88](@citet) describe the implementation of such; an algorithm for Poisson's equation on a staggered grid with Dirichlet, Neumann, and periodic boundary conditions. The method can be explained easily by

